04742nam a22006975i 9781442664852DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161995onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941171  a97814426648527 a10.3138/97814426648522doi  a(DE-B1597)465429  a(OCoLC)944178596  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD6100.P47 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a331.4/09713/6809041 aSangster, Joan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEarning Respect :bThe Lives of Working Women in Small Town Ontario, 1920-1960 /cJoan Sangster. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (334 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Gender and History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction: Placing the Story of Women's Work in Context -- t1. Peterborough: The 'Working Man's City' -- t2. Schooling Girls for Women's Work -- t3. Packing Muffets for a Living: Working Out the Gendered Division of Labour -- t4. Women's Work Culture, Women's Identities -- t5. Maintaining Respectability, Coping with Crises -- t6. Accommodation at Work -- t7. Resistance and Unionization -- t8. Doing Two Jobs: The Wage-Earning Mother in the Postwar Years -- tConclusion: From Working Daughter to Working Mother -- tAPPENDIX A: NOTE ON THE ORAL HISTORY SOURCES -- tAPPENDIX B: TABLES -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tPICTURE CREDITS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1920 and 1960 wage-earning women in factories and offices experienced dramatic shifts in their employment conditions, the result of both the Depression and the expansion of work opportunities during the Second World War. Earning Respect examines the lives of white and blue-collar women workers in Peterborough during this period and notes the emerging changes in their work lives, as working daughters gradually became working mothers.Joan Sangster focuses in particular on four large workplaces, examining the gendered division of labour, women's work culture, and the forces that encouraged women's accommodation and resistance on the job. She also connects women's wage work to their social and familial lives and to the larger community context, exploring wage-earning women's 'identities,' their attempts to cope with economic and family crises, the gendered definitions of working-class respectability, and the nature of paternalism in a small Ontario manufacturing city.Sangster draws upon oral histories as well as archival research as she traces the construction of class and gender relations in 'small town' industrialized Ontario in the mid-twentieth century. She uses this local study to explore key themes and theoretical debate in contemporary women's and working-class history.Winner of the 1995-1996 Harold Adams Innis Prize award by the Humanities and Social Sciences Federation of Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSexual division of laborzOntariozPeterboroughxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzOntariozPeterboroughxHistory. 0aWorking class womenzOntariozPeterboroughxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266485240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442664852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442664852.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruy